snippet.textDisplay:
It's a nice idea, but it's misguided without input from people who actually make ventilators for ICU - it's a nice example of a corporation suffering from the Dunning-Kruger Effect... with a slight whiff of techno-arrogance, and clear misunderstanding of human respiratory physiology & the pathophysiology of ARDS.

Anyone can make a device that 'forces air in' but for COVID-19 patients what is critical that their respiratory muscles needs to be what triggers the ventilator's inspiratory support. The ventilator then assists their effort. Patients who are 'force ventilated' have a very high mortality. You may as well just have a person squeezing a bag. The outcome will be the same.

PRVC, PCV & VCV are actually VERY BASIC ventilator modes and for a COVID-19 patient, they don't improve mortality. SIMV, PSV and similar is what you actually want. Patients NEED to be triggering the ventilator, and for that you need some very sophisticated flow sensors & software. Do that, then I'll leave a glowing review...

Disclosure: Anaesthesiologist.

Anyone can make a device that 'forces air in' but for COVID-19 patients what is critical that their respiratory muscles needs to be what triggers the ventilator's inspiratory support. The ventilator then assists their effort. Patients who are 'force ventilated' have a very high mortality. You may as well just have a person squeezing a bag. The outcome will be the same.

PRVC, PCV & VCV are actually VERY BASIC ventilator modes and for a COVID-19 patient, they don't improve mortality. SIMV, PSV and similar is what you actually want. Patients NEED to be triggering the ventilator, and for that you need some very sophisticated flow sensors & software. Do that, then I'll leave a glowing review...

Disclosure: Anaesthesiologist.

snippet.textDisplay:
Cudos Tesla!
It is essential that you try to use auto parts as much as possible to ease the burden on the medical supply chain. 
As I watched the video I observed a small error in your diagram: the heating should be in the inspiration arm best before the humidifier and not in the expiration arm. I guess you figured that out already 😏
Just to make sure, you are controlling the PEEP valve via software? Thats essential.

In the end of the video in the product requirements you check all the essential  boxes. I’d like that you to add flow and pressure triggered ventilation and  some lung recruitment procedures.
So please design over the air updates into the ventilator that you can add some software dependent procedures (like recruitment) later.

After this first wave of very sick patients the heath care system will have to cope for a prolonged period with this extremely contagious disease.
I also hope that Tesla would design a PAPR like the Versaflo from 3M. This is an essential part of PPE and it is in significant shortage. We as a medical community will need this for the next 12-18 months at least until a cure or vaccine for covid-19 is widely available.

An anesthesiologist and intensive care physician.

P.S. Don't touch your masks all the time you risk contamination. 😏

snippet.textDisplay:
As a Hardware and Software engineer who has designed ventilators in the past...

Did the third guy mention that they’re using an Exhalation valve? That’s a major concern.

Modern ventilators tend to stick with passive exhalation. Meaning, exhaling is not controlled by software or hardware, rather by Mother Nature.

Having an exhalation valve could potentially harm the patient in the event that it fails and locked close.
